soc.server.savegame

Class SavedGameModel

  • java.lang.Object
    • soc.server.savegame.SavedGameModel

  • public class SavedGameModel
extends java.lang.Object
    Data model for a game saved to/loaded from a file.

    To save, use the SavedGameModel(SOCGame, SOCServer) constructor and GameSaverJSON. To load, use SavedGameModel() and GameLoaderJSON. See those constructors' javadocs for usage details.

    This standalone model is cleaner than trying to serialize/deserialize SOCGame, SOCBoard, etc.

    Like the optional database, this data model has a modelVersion which may be older than the current JSettlers version. See MODEL_VERSION for lifecycle details.

    Some fields use custom serializers and/or deserializers: See SavedGameModel.PlayerInfo's @JsonAdapter field annotations and their TypeAdapters, those registered in GameLoaderJSON.initGson(), and SavedGameModel.CallbackClassTypeAdapterFactory.

    Since:
    2.3.00
    Author:
    Jeremy D Monin <jeremy@nand.net>

    • Field Detail

      • MODEL_VERSION

        public static final int MODEL_VERSION
        Current model schema version: 2400 for v2.4.00.

        Like the JSettlers database schema, this version may be older than the current JSettlers version. The model version should change only when its fields require changes which would prevent older JSettlers versions from understanding and loading a file using the new model.
        For example:

        • Adding a new important field
        • Using a new SOCGameElements.GEType or SOCPlayerElement.PEType constant to label an important game or player element value
        If the older version can't understand the loaded game without having the new field/constant, the model version must be increased.

        Within the same schema version:

        • New fields or SOCGameElements.GEType or SOCPlayerElement.PEType constants can be added, as long as they're optional and the game data is usable without them
        • When a newer JSettlers version loads an older file, added fields will be their type's default value (0, null, etc)
        • When an older JSettlers version loads a file with added fields which aren't in its copy of the model, the GSON parser ignores them
        • When an older JSettlers version loads a file which has SOCGameElements.GEType or SOCPlayerElement.PEType constant values which aren't in that version's copy of those enums, GameLoaderJSON ignores them
        createLoadedGame(SOCServer) will reject a loaded game if its modelVersion is newer than MODEL_VERSION, or if the game has features/options that it can't save. If you need to make a saved-game file for use by multiple JSettlers versions, save it from the oldest version.

        When MODEL_VERSION is changed, that will be documented here and in /doc/Versions.md. The earliest version number is 2300. If field formats change in the new schema, will add code to backwards-compatibility tests like TestLoadgame.testLoadModelVersion2300 to ensure the old format can still be reliably parsed.

        Changed in 2.4.00:

        • Players' dev cards (SavedGameModel.PlayerInfo.oldDevCards, newDevCards) are written as user-friendly type name strings like "ROADS", not ints. Can still read them as ints if needed. See field javadoc for details.
        • Game's devCardDeck uses those same name strings ("ROADS" etc)
        • Playing piece types (SOCPlayingPiece.getType() within SavedGameModel.PlayerInfo.pieces) are written as user-friendly type name strings like "SETTLEMENT", not ints. Can still read them as ints if needed. Pieces also omit writing specialVP field unless != 0, SOCShip omits isClosed field unless true.
        • Simple scenario support: Can save and load scenarios which have only a board layout and optionally game option _SC_SANY or _SC_SEAC, no other scenario game opts (option names starting with "_SC_"). Sets PlayerElements SCENARIO_SVP, SCENARIO_SVP_LANDAREAS_BITMASK. Adds SavedGameModel.PlayerInfo.specialVPInfo.
        • Adds SavedGameModel.PlayerInfo.earlyElements list to set before piece placement
        • SavedGameModel.PlayerInfo adds currentTradeOffer
        • Adds playerSeatLocks
        • gameOptions now sorted
        • While loading, robot player names are checked against server's connected bots to avoid naming conflicts and renamed using rand if needed

        Changed in 2.4.50:

        • Model version is still 2400
        • Adds dev card stats to SavedGameModel.PlayerInfo.elements: NUM_PLAYED_DEV_CARD_DISC, NUM_PLAYED_DEV_CARD_MONO, NUM_PLAYED_DEV_CARD_ROADS
        • Adds per-player list of dev cards played: SavedGameModel.PlayerInfo.playedDevCards
        • Adds SavedGameModel.TradeOffer.offeredAtDurationMillis
        • Earlier server versions will ignore these added fields while loading a savegame

      • warnHasHumanPlayerWithBotName

        public transient boolean warnHasHumanPlayerWithBotName
        To warn user while loading, this flag is set if the savegame has at least one human player who's named like a robot. (The savegame must be manually edited for this to happen; the server won't let human players with such names authenticate.) That can cause problems while resuming the game because of assumptions about timing of when robots (or players with robot names) are invited and join the loaded game.

        Checks the same name prefixes as SOCServer.checkNickname(String, Connection, boolean, boolean).

        Since:
        2.4.00

      • warnDevCardDeckHasUnknownType

        public transient boolean warnDevCardDeckHasUnknownType
        To warn user while loading, this flag is set if devCardDeck contains any card type which is <= SOCDevCardConstants.UNKNOWN or >= SOCDevCardConstants.MAXPLUSONE. If a dev card name string isn't recognized, it's put into the deck or players' dev cards as UNKNOWN. This flag is useful because unlike player inventories, the dev card deck is hidden.
        Since:
        2.4.00

      • devCardDeck

        public java.util.ArrayList<java.lang.Integer> devCardDeck
        Remaining unplayed dev cards, from SOCGame.getDevCardDeck(). If any unknown card types are found while loading, sets warnDevCardDeckHasUnknownType.

        In model schema 2.3.00, these were written as array of ints for dev card type constants. In 2.4.00 and higher, dev card types in each array are written as strings ("ROADS", "UNIV", etc) from SOCDevCard.getCardTypeName(int). For compatibility, unknown types are written as integer strings ("42"), and the adapter can read both integers and strings. See DevCardEnumListAdapter code for details.

        See Also:
        SavedGameModel.PlayerInfo.playedDevCards

      • SavedGameModel

        public SavedGameModel()
        Create an empty SavedGameModel to load a game file into. Once data is loaded and createLoadedGame(SOCServer) is called, state will temporarily be GameState.LOADING and SOCGame.savedGameModel will be this SGM. Call resumePlay(boolean) to continue play.

    • Method Detail

      • checkCanSave

        public static void checkCanSave(SOCGame ga)
                         throws SavedGameModel.UnsupportedSGMOperationException
        Can this game be saved to a SavedGameModel, or does it have options or features which haven't yet been implemented here?

        Currently unsupported:

        • Most scenario game options:
          If SOCGameOption "SC" != null, checks all game options:
          • "_SC_SANY" is OK
          • "_SC_SEAC" is OK
          • Any other scenario game option (keyname starts with "_SC_") is unsupported
          Throws SavedGameModel.UnsupportedSGMOperationException with message "admin.savegame.cannot_save.scen". SavedGameModel.UnsupportedSGMOperationException.param1 is scenario name, param2 is unsupported gameopt keyname.
        Parameters:
        ga - Game to check; not null
        Throws:
        SavedGameModel.UnsupportedSGMOperationException - if game has an option or feature not yet supported by SavedGameModel; Throwable.getMessage() will name the unsupported option/feature, ideally with an i18n key from "admin.savegame.cannot_save.*" but possibly as free-form text like "a unique resource type": Put a try-catch around your attempt to localize that key. Optional localization params are SavedGameModel.UnsupportedSGMOperationException.param1 and param2.
        See Also:
        checkCanLoad(SOCGameOptionSet)

      • findSeatsNeedingBots

        public boolean[] findSeatsNeedingBots()
        Check whether this game has any non-vacant seats which don't have a player. Typically those seats were human players when the game was saved, so they weren't automatically filled by robots when loading it, and no human player has sat down to take over. Caller should get bots or human players to sit at those seats.
        Returns:
        null if no more bots/players needed, or an array where array[pn] is true if seat with that player number still needs a player (glas.isMember(plName, gaName) is false for that non-vacant seat)

      • resumePlay

        public SOCGame resumePlay(boolean ignoreConstraints)
                   throws java.lang.UnsupportedOperationException,
                          java.util.MissingResourceException,
                          java.lang.IllegalStateException
        Resume play of a loaded game: Check any constraints, update gameState. Calls findSeatsNeedingBots() to check if the game still needs bots or human players at any seat before resuming. Clears SOCGame.savedGameModel field to null.

        If model's game state is GameState.GAME_OVER, skips constraint and seat/bot checks.

        Parameters:
        ignoreConstraints - If true, don't check any SavedGameModel.Constraints in the model
        Returns:
        game ready to play, with SOCGame.getGameState() same as when it was saved
        Throws:
        java.lang.UnsupportedOperationException - if gameState != GameState.LOADING or GameState.LOADING_RESUMING
        java.util.MissingResourceException - if non-vacant seats still need a bot or human player
        java.lang.IllegalStateException - if a constraint is not met

      • checkCanLoad

        public void checkCanLoad(SOCGameOptionSet knownOpts)
                  throws java.util.NoSuchElementException,
                         SOCGameOptionVersionException,
                         SavedGameModel.UnsupportedSGMOperationException
        Can the game data loaded into this SavedGameModel become a SOCGame in createLoadedGame(SOCServer), or does it have options or features which haven't yet been implemented here?

        See checkCanSave(SOCGame) for list of unsupported features checked here.

        This is needed because within the same MODEL_VERSION, a new JSettlers version could add fields or logic to support saving/loading more features; for example, certain scenarios but not all. The older version isn't able to load that saved game.

        Parameters:
        knownOpts - All Known Options, to parse game's SOCGameOptionSet; not null
        Throws:
        java.util.NoSuchElementException - if loaded data's model schema version (modelVersion field) is newer than the current MODEL_VERSION and important fields might not be in our version of the model. Exception's Throwable.getMessage() will be of the form: "model version 9170 newer than our version 2300"
        SOCGameOptionVersionException - if loaded data's gameMinVersion field is newer than the server's Version.versionNumber(). Exception's Throwable.getMessage() will be generic, but its SOCGameOptionVersionException.gameOptsVersion will be gameMinVersion
        SavedGameModel.UnsupportedSGMOperationException - if game has an option or feature not yet supported by createLoadedGame(SOCServer). Throwable.getMessage() will name the unsupported option/feature or the problematic game opt from SOCGameOption.parseOptionsToMap(String, SOCGameOptionSet). In that case, Throwable.getMessage() will contain that method's IllegalArgumentException message and Throwable.getCause() will not be null. Optional localization params are SavedGameModel.UnsupportedSGMOperationException.param1 and param2.

      • createLoadedGame

        void createLoadedGame(SOCServer srv)
               throws java.lang.IllegalStateException,
                      java.util.NoSuchElementException,
                      SOCGameOptionVersionException,
                      SavedGameModel.UnsupportedSGMOperationException,
                      java.lang.IllegalArgumentException
        Try to create the SOCGame and its objects based on data loaded into this SGM. Calls checkCanLoad(SOCGameOptionSet). If successful (no exception thrown), game state will be GameState.LOADING.

        Doesn't add to game list glas or check whether game name is already taken, because SOCServer.createOrJoinGame(Connection, int, String, SOCGameOptionSet, SOCGame, int) is better able to do so and can rename the loaded game if needed to avoid name collisions.

        Examines game and player data. Might set warnHasHumanPlayerWithBotName, warnDevCardDeckHasUnknownType flags.

        Parameters:
        srv - Server reference to check for bot name collisions; not null. Calls srv.createNewGameList() and sets glas. Any bot players in the loaded game data with same names as those logged into the server will be renamed to avoid problems during random bot assignment while joining the game.
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalStateException - if this method's already been called
        java.util.NoSuchElementException - if loaded data's model schema version (modelVersion field) is newer than the current MODEL_VERSION; see checkCanLoad(SOCGameOptionSet) for details
        SOCGameOptionVersionException - if loaded data's gameMinVersion field is newer than the server's Version.versionNumber(); see checkCanLoad(SOCGameOptionSet) for details
        SavedGameModel.UnsupportedSGMOperationException - if loaded game model has an option or feature not yet supported by createLoadedGame(); see checkCanLoad(SOCGameOptionSet) for details
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if there's a problem while creating the loaded game. Throwable.getCause() will have the exception thrown by the SOCGame/SOCPlayer method responsible. Catch subclass SOCGameOptionVersionException before this one. Also thrown if playerSeats.length != created game's SOCGame.maxPlayers.
